7":"1300–1347","1295–1360":"1295–1360","12 FEB 1407":"12 February 1407","29 April 1360":"29 April 1360","1330":"1330","1295":"1295","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","1326":"1326","1347":"1347","1334":"1334","1344":"1344","1300":"1300","1365":"1365","1332":"1332","1321":"1321","1353":"1353","about 1320":"about 1320","1407":"1407","28 FEB 1347":"28 February 1347","Hanged, Drawn & Quartered in London, Middlesex, England":"Middlesex, England, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland","Menteith, Perth, Scotland":"Perthshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Graham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from Grantham in Lincolnshire, recorded in Domesday Book as <i>Graham</i> (as well as <i>Grantham</i>, <i>Grandham</i>, and <i>Granham</i>). See also   Grantham  .","Irish (especially Ulster): in Ireland <i>Graham</i> is generally the Scottish name, but it has additionally been adopted as an Anglicized form of both <b>Ó Creacháin</b> (see   Crehan  ) and <b>Ó Gormghaile</b> (see   Gormley  ).","History: The surname Graham was taken to Scotland at the beginning of the 12th century by the Norman baron William de Graham, holder of the manor of Grantham in Lincolnshire, from whom many if not all modern bearers are probably descended. The chief of Clan Graham is the Duke of Montrose."],"variants":[{"name":"Greim","meanings":["South German: from a short form of a compound personal name beginning with the element <i>grīm</i> ‘mask, helmet’.","Scottish: variant of   Graham  ."]},{"name":"Grahm","meanings":["(1997: 107;2007: 460; 2010: NA)","Scottish (Lanarkshire and northern England): shortened form of   Graham  ."]},{"name":"Grantham","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire and East Yorkshire): habitational name from Grantham in Lincolnshire, of uncertain origin. The final element is Old English <i>hām</i> ‘homestead’; the first may be Old English <i>grand</i> ‘gravel’ or perhaps a personal name <i>Granta</i>, which probably originated as a byname meaning ‘snarler’. See also   Graham  ."]},{"name":"Grahame","meanings":["(1997: 113;2007: 164; 2010: NA)","Scottish: variant of   Graham  . — Note: The population figure published by the US Census Bureau for this surname in the year 2000 is as high as 261, while the figure for 2010 is supposedly lower than 100."]}]},{"name":"Earl","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>e(o)rl</i> ‘earl’, a traditional English title of nobility equivalent in rank to French and Norman   Count  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Earle","meanings":["English: variant of   Earl  ."]},{"name":"Harle","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Dieter, Johann, Kurt.","South German (<b>Härle</b>): nickname from a diminutive of Middle High German <i>hār</i> ‘hair’.","English (northern) and Scottish: habitational name from Kirkharle and Little Harle in Northumberland (earlier simply <i>Herle</i>, <i>Harle</i>), possibly named from an Old English personal name <i>Herela</i> (a derivative of various compound names with the first element <i>here</i> ‘army’) + Old English <i>lēah</i> ‘wood, clearing’."]},{"name":"Earls","meanings":["English: variant of   Earl   with genitival <i>-s</i>, denoting someone who was a member of an earl's household, or, with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. In Ireland, when this is not the English name, it is from Gaelic <b>Mac an Iarla</b> ‘son of the earl’."]},{"name":"Hearl","meanings":["English: variant of   Earl   with prosthetic <i>H-</i>."]},{"name":"Count","meanings":["English: nickname from Anglo-Norman French <i>counte</i> ‘count’ (Old French <i>conte</i>, from Latin <i>comes</i>, <i>comitem</i>); a title of French and Norman nobility, ranking as equivalent to English   Earl  ."]},{"name":"Earll","meanings":["English (Kent): variant of   Earl  ."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Sung, Jung, Yong, Chang, Kwang, Sang, Dong, Hyun, Jae, Jin, Kyung, Jong, Chong, Chung, Byung, Jeong, Pyong, Myong, Hak, Jin Hwan, Sook, Yeong, Choon.","Korean: variant of   O  .","Japanese: variant of <b>Ō</b> (see   O  )."],"variants":[{"name":"O","meanings":["(1997: 122;2010: NA)","Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Bo Young, Chae, Chong Hwan, Dong Kun, Ho, Hwan, Hyun, Jong, Jung, Ki Soon, Kwang.  Korean Min, Chong, Chol, Jung Ho, Myong, Sa, Sung Kyun.","Korean (오; Chinese character: 吳): historically, there were two Chinese characters for the O surname, but by the late Koryŏ period (14th century  AD ), one of them had disappeared. Some records indicate that there are as many as 210 different clans for the remaining character, but only sixteen can be positively documented. All sixteen of these clans originate from the same ancestor, O Ch’ŏm (吳 瞻), who migrated to Korea from China during the reign of Shilla's King Chijŭng (500–514  AD ). <i>O</i> is a common surname throughout Korea. Compare   Oh  ."]}]},{"name":"Menteith","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from the earldom and province of <i>Menteith</i> in Perthshire, named in Gaelic as ‘hill pasture (above) the Teith’, from <i>monadh</i> ‘hill pasture’ + <i>Teith</i>, a river name of obscure origin. This name was introduced to Ulster at the time of the Plantation in the 17th century, where it is now quite numerous in certain areas, particularly Tyrone."],"variants":[{"name":"Montooth","meanings":["Probably an altered form of Scottish   Monteith  ."]},{"name":"Mantooth","meanings":["Probably an altered form of Scottish   Monteith   or<b>Mantach</b>, a nickname from Gaelic <i>manntach</i> ‘stammering’(also ‘toothless’ in Irish), of which one early Welsh recorded form is<i>Mantath</i>."]},{"name":"Montierth","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Monteith  ."]},{"name":"Montieth","meanings":["Scottish (Lanarkshire): variant of   Monteith   This form of the surname is rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Graham Earl of Menteith was born in 1344, in Scotland, his father, John Graham of Dundaff, 9th Earl of Menteith, was 44 and his mother, Mary II, Countess of Menteith, was 50. He had at least 1 son with Second Countess of Menteith. He died on 12 February 1407, at the age of 63."},"et":{"1344–12 FEB 1407":"1344–12. veebruar 1407","1321–1353":"1321–1353","1326–Male":"1326–Surnud","1330–Female":"1330–Surnud","1332–1365":"1332–1365","1334–1380":"1334–1380","1344–1407":"1344–1407","–Female":"Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1300–1347":"1300–1347","1295–1360":"1295–1360","12 FEB 1407":"12. veebruar 1407","29 April 1360":"29. aprill 1360","1330":"1330","1295":"1295","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","1326":"1326","1347":"1347","1334":"1334","1344":"1344","1300":"1300","1365":"1365","1332":"1332","1321":"1321","1353":"1353","about 1320":"umbes 1320","1407":"1407","28 FEB 1347":"28. veebruar 1347","Hanged, Drawn & Quartered in London, Middlesex, England":"Middlesex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Sco